/*
  The IEEE 754 standard defines +0.0 as all bits set to zero: 
  +0.0 (float, 32 bits):
  Sign Exponent Mantissa
  0    00000000 00000000000000000000000
  So, zeroinitializer and 0.0 are practically equivalent.

   The nuance is that IEEE 754 also defines -0.0 (sign=1, remainder zeros), 
   which is a different bit value even though +0.0 == -0.0 is numerically true. 
   zeroinitializer always returns +0.0.    
*/
{
    float f;
    print(f); // 0
}
